{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Nikola Vlašić | image = Nikola Vlašić.jpg | image_size = | caption = Vlašić with [[PFC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]] in 2018 | fullname = Nikola Vlašić<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/612828 |title=Updated squads for 2017/18 Premier League confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=2 February 2018 |accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|10|4|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Split, Croatia|Split]], Croatia | height = 1.78 m | position = [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|Attacking midfielder]] | currentclub = [[PFC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]] (on loan from [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]) | clubnumber = 8 | youthyears1 = 2006–2009 | youthclubs1 = [[NK Omladinac Vranjic|Omladinac Vranjic]] | youthyears2 = 2010–2014 | youthclubs2 = [[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]] | years1 = 2014–2017 | clubs1 = [[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]] | caps1 = 86 | goals1 = 11 | years2 = 2017– | clubs2 = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] | caps2 = 12 | goals2 = 0 | years3 = 2018– | clubs3 = → [[PFC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]] (loan) | caps3 = 15 | goals3 = 4 <!--National league stats only in the infobox. No Champions League, no Cup. --> | nationalyears1 = 2012–2013 | nationalteam1 = [[Croatia national under-16 football team|Croatia U16]] | nationalcaps1 = 8 | nationalgoals1 = 1 | nationalyears2 = 2013 | nationalteam2 = [[Croatia national under-17 football team|Croatia U17]] | nationalcaps2 = 8 | nationalgoals2 = 1 | nationalyears3 = 2014 | nationalteam3 = [[Croatia national under-18 football team|Croatia U18]] | nationalcaps3 = 2 | nationalgoals3 = 1 | nationalyears4 = 2015 | nationalteam4 = [[Croatia national under-19 football team|Croatia U19]] | nationalcaps4 = 3 | nationalgoals4 = 0 | nationalyears5 = 2015– | nationalteam5 = [[Croatia national under-21 football team|Croatia U21]] | nationalcaps5 = 12 | nationalgoals5 = 4 | nationalyears6 = 2017– | nationalteam6 = [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] | nationalcaps6 = 4 | nationalgoals6 = 0 | club-update = 2 March 2019 | nationalteam-update = 18 November 2018 }} '''Nikola Vlašić''' ({{IPA-sh|nǐkoɫa ʋɫâʃitɕ|hr}};<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hjp.znanje.hr/index.php?show=search_by_id&id=eF1gUBk%3D|title=Nìkola|quote=Nìkola|website=Hrvatski jezični portal|accessdate=2018-03-17|language=sh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hjp.znanje.hr/index.php?show=search_by_id&id=f19vXBJ%2B|title=Vlȁškā|quote=Vlȁšić|website=Hrvatski jezični portal|accessdate=2018-03-17|language=sh}}</ref> born 4 October 1997) is a Croatian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as an [[Midfielder (association football)#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]] for [[Russian Premier League]] club [[PFC CSKA Moscow]] on loan from [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and the [[Croatia national football team|Croatia national team]].
In 2014, Vlašić made list of the world's top 40 footballers born in 1997, compiled by ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/ng-interactive/2014/oct/14/next-generation-2014-40-of-the-best-young-talents-in-world-football|title=Next Generation 2014: 40 of the best young talents in world football|date=14 October 2014|work=The Guardian|accessdate=14 October 2014}}</ref>
==Club career== ===Hajduk Split=== Born in [[Split, Croatia|Split]] to the family of the athletics coach [[Joško Vlašić]], as the younger brother of the world champion [[high jump]]er [[Blanka Vlašić]], Nikola's future football career was viewed as a "project" by his father, who started training him personally ever since he was four years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vecernji.hr/ostali-sportovi/josko-vlasic-nije-nikola-projekt-za-zaradu-922719|title=Joško Vlašić: Nije Nikola projekt za zaradu|date=22 February 2014|publisher=Večernji list|language=Croatian|accessdate=22 February 2014}}</ref>
Vlašić went on to join the [[NK Omladinac Vranjic]] academy, before he was brought to [[HNK Hajduk Split]], aged 12. He made his debut for the Croatia U16 national football team at the age of 14,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hns-cff.hr/en/players/119418/nikola-vlasic/|title=Statistics - Caps: Nikola Vlašić|publisher=Croatian Football Federation|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref> playing regularly with older teammates at U17 and U18 levels as well. He excelled at youth club level as well, and in the 2013–2014 season he formed a potent midfield partnership for the Hajduk U17 team with [[Andrija Balić]], which resulted in the team finishing the first half of the season in first place, without a single loss. The two then received and signed professional contracts,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.24sata.hr/nogomet/potpisali-vlasic-hairlahovic-i-balic-ocekujemo-puno-od-njih-349501|title=Potpisali Vlašić, Hairlahović i Balić: Očekujemo puno od njih|date=16 January 2014|publisher=24sata|language=Croatian|accessdate=16 January 2014}}</ref> and were moved to the U19 team, where he played regularly.
He made his first team debut in the [[UEFA Europa League]] qualifying match on 17 July 2014, playing in the away match against [[Dundalk F.C.]]. Scoring on his debut, he became [[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]]'s youngest scorer in international competitions, aged 16 years and 9 months, 2 months less than the previous record holder [[Mario Tičinović]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gol.dnevnik.hr/clanak/nogomet/rijeka-protiv-fradija-na-kantridi-hajduk-u-irskoj-split-na-parku-mladezi---344500.html|title=Hajduk slavio u Irskoj: Nikola Vlašić najmlađi strijelac 'bijelih' u povijesti!|date=17 July 2014|publisher=Gol.hr|language=Croatian|accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> That season, Vlašić went on to make 37 appearances in all competitions, scoring four goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hajduk.hr/prva-momcad/nikola-vlasic/8|title=Prva momčad • HNK Hajduk Split|website=hajduk.hr}}</ref>
On 30 June 2016, Hajduk announced that Vlašić had been appointed vice-captain of the club, with [[Lovre Kalinić]] continuing to be the captain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hajduk.hr/vijest/kalinic-je-kapetan--a-nikola-vlasic-njegov-nasljednik/7423|title=Kalinić je kapetan, a Nikola Vlašić njegov nasljednik!|website=hajduk.hr}}</ref> As Kalinić was on extended holidays as a result of being part of the Croatian squad at [[UEFA Euro 2016]], Vlašić captained Hajduk for the first time on 14 July 2016, the season opening fixture; a 2–2 away draw against [[CS Municipal Studențesc Iași]] in the second round of the [[2016–17 UEFA Europa League qualifying phase and play-off round|2016–17 Europa League qualifying phase]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2017/matches/round=2000789/match=2020096/postmatch/index.html|title=UEFA Europa League 2016/17 - History - CSMS laşi-Hajduk Split – UEFA.com|first=|last=uefa.com|website=Uefa.com}}</ref> Despite his tender age, Vlašić would captain the side four further times that season.
===Everton=== On 31 August 2017, Vlašić signed a five-year deal with [[Premier League]] club [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] for a fee of around £10m, the highest fee [[Hajduk Split]] have ever received.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNulty|first1=Phil|title=Nikola Vlasic: Everton seal £10m deal for Hajduk Split forward|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41078149|accessdate=14 September 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=31 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.evertonfc.com/news/2017/08/31/blues-sign-vlasic|title=Blues Sign Vlasic|date=31 August 2017|publisher=Everton FC|accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref> Vlašić impressed Everton manager [[Ronald Koeman]] and director of football Steve Walsh when Everton and Hajduk faced each other in the [[2017–18 UEFA Europa League]] play-off round.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McNulty|first1=Phil|title=Nikola Vlasic: Everton seal £10m deal for Hajduk Split forward|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41078149|website=BBC|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref> Vlasic scored his first goal for [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on his debut at Goodison Park to put Everton ahead against [[Apollon Limassol]] in the [[Europa League]], in the 66th minute on 28 September 2017.
===CSKA Moscow=== On 15 August 2018, Russian club [[PFC CSKA Moscow]] announced that Vlašić joined them on loan for the 2018–19 season.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[PFC CSKA Moscow]]|url=https://en.pfc-cska.com/news/team-news/nikola-vlai-joins-pfc-cska/|title=Nikola Vlašić joins PFC CSKA|date=15 August 2018|language=English}}</ref> On 2 October 2018 Vlašić scored the winning goal against title holders Real Madrid on the 2nd minute in the 2018/19 UCL.
==International career== ===Youth=== {{Empty section|date=January 2018}}
===Senior=== On 28 May 2017. Vlašić made his debut with [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] in a [[friendly match]] against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] after being named in the starting line-up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kwese.espn.com/football/report?gameId=475660|title=Croatia beat Mexico to spoil Hernandez's record-breaking night|website=ESPN|last=Marshall|first=Tom|date=28 May 2017|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref>
On 18 November 2018, he provided an assist to [[Andrej Kramarić]] in a [[UEFA Nations League]] match against [[England national football team|England]] for a 0-1 lead, which Croatia eventually lost 2-1.
==Personal life== He is the brother of Croatian athlete [[Blanka Vlašić]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://daswunderkind.net/190712-nikola-blanka-josko-vlasic-croatia-wonderkid/|title=Nikola Vlasic: Leaping out of sister's shadow|date=19 July 2014|publisher=}}</ref>
